      "side": 1,
      "message": "So the issue was that skia.h.d from previous versions started with \u0027skia.h:\u0027 instead of \u0027gen/skia.h:\u0027. As a result, ninja gave the error \"ninja: error: expected depfile \u0027gen/skia.h.d\u0027 to mention \u0027gen/skia.h\u0027, got \u0027skia.h\u0027\" and quit with exit code 1.\n\nI seems quite awkward to recover from this. Would it be better if ninja ignored or warned on such an invalid depfile and then consider the target out of date? This would at least allow the target to re-run and try fixing up its depfile. Maybe this isn\u0027t possible because the depfile might be a non-generated edited outside the build thing? Or even generated by another build step, like https://github.com/ninja-build/ninja/issues/1090 .\n\nIs there a reason why ninja can\u0027t just suck up the depfile and then delete it (similar to how it normally seems to with the compiler)? In other words, use ninja\u0027s \u0027deps \u003d gcc\u0027 with \u0027depfile\u0027. It seems gn surfaces this for toolchains, but not for actions...\n\nInterestingly, if the depfile is edited externally or generated by the build anyway, the what ninja is doing is correct. You\u0027ll need to fix the file or the build and then that will regenerate the depfile and things should be good. However, if the build step itself is going to create the depfile, then it needs to be handled like the compiler depfile, where ninja sucks it in and deletes the file (and then errors and the target remains dirty if the depfile produced is invalid).",
